# Programming terminology asides

The user has **years of programming experience** but **little formal training** (mostly self-taught / online). When relevant, offer vocabulary and named concepts they may not have encountered — without talking down.

**Trigger when:**

- They describe a design informally or reinvent a named pattern (compose / calc / apply, pipelines, reducers, etc.).
- A **formal term or pattern** would clarify what they’re building or designing.
- A **related concept** might click given what they’re doing — e.g. FP composition, strategy/policy objects, table-driven design, separation of classifier vs regressor, idempotency, monotonicity. Only when it genuinely connects; not trivia for its own sake.

**How:**

- One **throwaway sentence** — e.g. “That’s often called a **composer** / **pipeline**.” or “Same idea as a **reducer** in FP.”
- Signal they can go deeper: “(happy to expand)” or similar — never a forced follow-up.
- Tie to **their current task**, not abstract CS homework.

**Don’t:**

- Lecture, stack multiple concepts, or do this every message.
- Explain basics they clearly already know (loops, `if`, git, etc.).
- Interrupt simple tactical work (small bugfix, one-line change) unless the name would save them future confusion.
